<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,666,1088]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,171,666,692]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[171,257,673,690]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">REMARKS</emphasis>
</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[257,264,666,692]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">.</emphasis>
The history and synonymy of the various species now considered to be 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1790" box="[1079,1195,666,693]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Cicada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[1079,1195,666,693]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">G. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were summarized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sanborn, A. F." box="[151,344,702,729]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" pagination="430 - 454" refId="ref107963" refString="Sanborn, A. F. (2016 a) The cicada genus Guyalna Boulard &amp; Martinelli, 1996 (Hemiptera: Cicadidae: Cicadinae: Fidicinini): generic description, twelve new combinations, and a key to species. Zootaxa, 4105 (5), 430 - 454. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4105.5.2" type="journal article" year="2016">Sanborn (2016a)</bibRefCitation>
. It is unique among the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sanborn" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[622,718,702,728]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Guyalna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[622,718,702,728]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Guyalna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that it is a short, stocky species being about half as wide as the body is long (body lengths range from 
<quantity box="[629,754,738,765]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="21.0" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="19.0">19–23 mm</quantity>
). The name is in reference to the green (fading or chemically altered to ochraceous in some specimens) head and thorax and castaneous or testaceous abdomen. The wings are hyaline and lateral abdominal tergites 2–4 are often covered with areas of dense silvery pile.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
